body:
The following is the problematic code `test.v`, which I have minimized (deleting any line will cause the unexpected behavior to disappear):

```verilog
`timescale 1ns/1ps
module tjzeyzoicm ();

    reg  [27:5] in0;
    reg [26:11] in1;
    wire  [24:14] wire_0;
    wire [26:5] out1;
    wire _085_;
    wire _082_;
    wire [10:0] _092_;
    wire [9:0] _028_;

    initial begin
        in0 = 6902127;
        in1 = 10000;
        #10;
        $display("out1: %0d\n", out1);
    end

    assign _028_ = ~ { 9'h000, in0[23] };
    assign _092_[1] = 1'h0;
    assign { _092_[10:2], _092_[0] } = _028_;
    assign wire_0 = _092_;
    assign _082_ = | wire_0[18:17];
    assign _085_ = _082_ ? in1[11] : 1'h0;
    assign out1 = { 21'h000000, _085_ };
endmodule
```

The issue can be reproduced by running the following commands:

```
verilator --binary -Wno-lint --timing test.v
./obj_dir/Vtest
```

The program outputs:

```
out1: 10000
```

However, based on the code of `test.v`, the assignment `assign out1 = { 21'h000000, _085_ };` only allows the least significant bit to vary. Therefore, the output value of `out1` should only be `0` or `1`, but not the value of `in1`.

Using the `-fno-expand` option eliminates the error, so this issue might be related to https://github.com/verilator/verilator/issues/5963. However, the difference is that in this issue, all involved variables are unsigned, so the root cause might be different.

